IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos—Lagarde said she is open to the possibility of serving another five years as the International Monetary Fund (IMF) chief.
She should remain in her position.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than her, and the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she herself started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, assuming leadership of an institution facing numerous crises.
The 2008 global financial crisis and its subsequent economic aftermath undermined the credibility of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus."
Lagarde's leadership helped restore the IMF's reputation.
Many eyes were turned toward her personal qualities — as they should be.
She admitted, was strong, warm, and touching.
Officials from various countries who met with her (often in delicate situations) repeatedly expressed that she was courageous in speaking the difficult realities, while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for an institution leader who must negotiate the terms of an agreement rather than dominate everything.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, or else they must establish firewalls to prevent financial contagion. The advice was harsh but ears were not offended; the Europeans followed it.
Similarly, she called for IMF support to be provided to some countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not particularly good at innovation, and is usually not filled with passion.
Lagarde began to change this.
In this process, she gave this institution, which often prescribes harsh remedies, a human face.
For example, helping to manage the refugee crisis in the Middle East was not originally within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its program, allowing the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist those displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over one million people are living in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak hit West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF in using available funds to grant debt relief to affected countries, enabling them to improve the treatment of doctors and nurses — this was the first time the IMF had used its own capital in such a manner.
In addition, Lagarde recognized the three most important challenges facing the world today and took action to address them.
First, she strongly advocated for increasing the participation of women in the workforce, serving as a role model that exemplifies the value of having women in leadership positions.
In various countries ranging from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop squandering such a vast talent resource — and thereby realize economic potential.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a matter of basic fairness.
IMF's research highlights a direct link between reducing income inequality and promoting economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to demonstrate this, but its position makes the issue appear more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde has personally been committed to promoting this point, which has been crucial in raising its urgency.
Third, Lagarde played an important role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change—some of which could cause alarming destructive effects.
For example, automation will continue to increase the efficiency of manufacturing and reduce its costs, but it also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth will be less than in the past.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth our understanding and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF the core of this work.
Critics would say it's time for developing countries to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th European in a row to hold this position, and Europe's possession of such a privilege is already difficult to justify in today's world.
Some people might argue that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not yielded significant results, proving that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Some people would also point out that she faces charges related to financial scandals in France, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
Following her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn's deep involvement in a scandal, critics believed that the IMF could never again be distracted by similar incidents.
Let's analyze these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside of Europe and the United States.
But the purpose of ending this Western privilege is to base the leader selection process on competence rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best choice to be the IMF's managing director, and emerging powers such as the BRICS countries (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) did not jointly put forward an alternative candidate.
Having an European hold the IMF's leadership position might have been one of the favorable factors behind the IMF's decision at the end of last year to include the Chinese yuan in the currency basket used to determine the value of the Special Drawing Rights.
Moreover, Lagarde demonstrated impressive political flexibility, ultimately persuading both the Republican and Democratic parties in the U.S. Congress to approve IMF governance reforms. These reforms not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal against financial crises but also more accurately reflected the evolving dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRIC countries have now entered the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the Greek issue, last year Lagarde made some blunt, personal-style comments — which some considered inappropriate.
But she was certainly not the culprit who brought economic hardship to the Greeks. Her tenure at the IMF clearly demonstrated that no IMF Managing Director in the organization's history had done as much as she did to lead the IMF in alleviating the suffering of people during crises.
Finally, the French prosecutors opposed the charges against Lagarde, and Lagarde at most was only slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven herself to be exactly the kind of leader committed to making the IMF adapt to the 21st century.
She should be given a chance to have a complete and fulfilling experience.
